04480nam a22005055i 9780773549722DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735497227 a10.1515/97807735497222doi  a(DE-B1597)657131  a(OCoLC)973044190  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a909.83/12231 aJohnston, Donald J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMissing the Tide :bGlobal Governments in Retreat /cDonald J. Johnston. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b22 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tThe Prime Minister Calls -- tThe Genius of Jean Monnet and the Marshall Plan -- tEurope Listing, but Afloat -- tRussia: An Opportunity Bungled -- tStatistics: Their Uses and Abuses -- tThe Economists and the Dismal Science -- tCentral Bankers and Their Controversies -- tAusterity versus Growth – Ideology versus Common Sense -- tBubbles in our Future? Certainly! -- tSustainable Development: A Recipe with Too Many Ingredients -- tClimate Change: Unrealistic Expectations -- tThe Scourge of Corruption, Public and Private -- tShaping Globalization: Dogged by Failure -- tThe Democratic Imperative: Perhaps Not for All? -- tCan the Tide Return? -- tAppendix: The Benefits of International Conferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1990s were a decade characterized by optimism about a great future that lay ahead for generations to follow. Major challenges were approached with a realization that the world leadership had the capacity not only to meet them, but to turn them into unprecedented opportunities for global social and economic progress. In Missing the Tide, Donald Johnston demonstrates that none of these opportunities achieved their objectives, and in some cases failed completely. Scrutinizing some of the most significant unfulfilled hopes, he looks at the failure of the West to engage effectively with a democratic Russia after the fall of the Berlin Wall, the European Union’s fractious path to intending to become history’s largest and most competitive economy, the expansion of the Marshall Plan concept to regions fractured by division and conflict, the diminishing prospect of global free trade and investment to stimulate economic growth and increase prosperity in the developing world, the absence of coordinated international actions to combat climate change, the pervasive corruption in corporate governance undermining healthy capitalism, and the growing threats to democracy. Sifting through the economic, social, and environmental wreckage of the past twenty years, Johnston reflects on the failures and frustrations of international public policy. Can this rapid decline be arrested and reversed? In assessing the impotency of the international community to meet these challenges, Missing the Tide extracts some lessons to be learned and looks with cautious optimism to the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld politicsy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077354972240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773549722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773549722/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles